Mostly minor cleanup.
Fix the merge screwup where changes were make on Niepce and not pushed for about a year (sigh).

Implementation of a relatively easy to use JPanel which can be the target of drag-and-drop operations.
Gowing support for serializing and deserializing arrays of primitives and arrays of Java container classes (e.g. Integer, Double, String, etc). Still missing support for arrays of GowingPackable objects. Considerable cleanup.
Start the process of turning the SortedSetExample.java class into a reasonable Gowing-aware example.

Simplified flavor handler facility provided by AbstractDataFlavorHandler and BasicFlavorHandlers (avoids a lot of repetitive typing when implementing drag-and-drop stuff.
Lots of xxxValue helper methods in GowingPackedEntityBundle.java to avoid need to invoke getNullableField and getNotNullField in order to get to its xxxValue methods.
Lots of cleanup in Gowing and elsewhere.
Avoid a common Gowing bug by making failing to collect a super class's bundle much more likely to provoke a fatal error in Gowing (mostly involves broader use of @NotNull for parameters that pass bundles around).

Implement a mechanism for filtering out certain log lines in the Logger facility.
Implement a method in ObtuseUtil which returns the name of a specified InputEvent modifier key mask bit.
Fix a typo in the TreeSorter class's Javadocs and use the new computeIfAbsent mechanism when adding a new value.
Lots of cleanup based on code analysis.
Get rid of some IntelliJ warnings in the Ranges class.
Move the linear layout manager facility from the Burke2 project to the Pipestone project.
Move the linear layout manager facility from the Burke2 project to the Pipestone project.

Lots of cleanup.
Temporary kludge to make things work on non-Mac operating systems (declare hollow versions of the various Apple classes).

Implement a Scrollable which handles entities of differing sizes while seeking to ensure but not guarantee that the first visible entity starts at the top of the view.
Add some of the Apache text edit distance classes.
Various cleanup.
Almost entirely cleanup.

Rework the various ObtuseUtil.enquote... methods.

Add parsing for more date formats in FlexibleDateTransmogrifier. Rework the parse method in ObtuseApproximateCalendarDate to use FlexibleDateTransmogrifier for most styles of dates (date ranges don't use it yet). Cleanup.
Implement metadata handlers in Gowing. Make accidentally encountering null super bundle pointers in GPEB's much less likely. Cleanup.

Specify the nullability of arrays separately from their contents in all sorts of places. Add lots and lots of final, @NotNull, and @Nullable attributes.
Implement reasonably easy to use button and combo-box based selector panels.
The usual mountain of cleanup.

Basic sanity returns in my button and combo-box wrapping classes.
The ButtonSelectorPanel class and the ComboBoxSelectorPanel class both derive from the SelectorPanel class which itself derives from the JPanel class. I had the SelectorPanel constructor setting its layout manager to a BorderLayout instance and then add a couple of things to its super-class (i.e. to the JPanel). I had also at some point recently, had the ButtonSelectorPanel constructor set its layout manager to a different BorderLayout instance and then add a couple of things to the JPanel (i.e. its super-super-class).
The result was that when the JPanel was rendered, the things that the SelectorPanel class added to the JPanel did not appear. When I listed out the contents of the JPanel and found that the now invisible things were actually in the JPanel, things got just a bit mysterious.
Well . . . it turns out that the BorderLayout manager keeps track of what it is supposed to layout as things are added to the Container instance that it is responsible for. This means that when you assign a BorderLayout instance as the layout manager for a Container, anything already in the Container before said assignment is ignored by the BorderLayout instance. The result is that things which are actually in the Container don't get laid out and thus don't get rendered.
Sigh.
Moral of this story is that one should assign the BorderLayout manager to a Container BEFORE one puts anything in the Container (unless one is looking for an roughly three day long "learning opportunity" like the one that I just went through).
P.S. This commit also adds some not all that well thought out "tell me about this container and its contents" utility methods to the LinearLayoutManager class. These will (hopefully) get cleaned up soon to the point where they are actually useful.

Lots of cleanup of the selector panels. Implement a new BorderLayoutPanel class that assigns itself a BorderLayout instance and then refuses to let anyone change its layout manager. This avoids some very strange behaviour that can result if one is not careful about when BorderLayout instances are assigned to a panel that is intended to use that layout manager. See the new BorderLayoutPanel class' Javadocs for more info.
Birth of the ObtuseCollections class (more to come later). Otherwise, mostly cleanup.

Major cleanup in the wrapped selector panels stuff. Advent of the ContextualToString class which facilitates providing different toString results depending on the context. Provide some basic support for customized toString results from ObtuseKeyword instances (note that this is customized toString results like providing mixed case keyword names; it is not contextual customized toString - each ObtuseKeyword instance will produce the exact same toString result although the developer gets to decide what that result will be when the ObtuseKeyword instance is created).

Add fairly basic "regular verbose" and "super verbose" mechanism to make it a bit easier to figure out why the "finish unpacking" phase of a Gowing unpack operation is failing.
Add an unchecked GowingUnpackingDeadlockedException which is thrown when the "finish unpacking" phase of a Gowing unpack operation reaches a point where a round of finishing doesn't reduce the number of unfinished unpackables. This is usually because two packables are waiting for each other to finish (generally if not always because one or both of the packables have a "cannot finish until the other is finished" dependency that doesn't really need to be there, or the finishing strategy being used is flawed - roughly speaking, if it was possible to build the data structure one step-at-a-time in the first place then there must be a way to unpack it while finishing it one-step-at-a-time).
Cleanup of various aspects of the Gowing facility and elsewhere.

Implement the ability to construct/initialize a WrappedButtonSelectorPanel with a particular button pre-selected and a WrappedComboBoxSelectorPanel with a particular choice pre-selected.
Fix a subtle bugin GowingPackableKeyValuePair where its ability to finish an instance was incorrectly dependent upon its value field being finished. This created an unbreakable finish-dependency loop during an unpacking operation.
Cleanup.
Massive cleanup of commented out dead software (about 2,500 lines across almost 100 source files).

Add an AboutBox form that makes it easy to implement a simple GUI "about this application" popup.
A relatively modest amount of relatively minor cleanup.

Move away from providing a sized array to the Collection.toArray() methods (no longer faster than just providing a zero-length array of the correct type).
Add a makeRelative method to the AbsolutePath class that returns a RelativePath containing all the segments in the AbsolutePath minus the first root node segment.
Major cleanup in the RelativePath class:
- cleanup the various concat methods to provide better orthogonality - implement a segment-by-segment compareTo method (eliminates the need for a string representation of the path although we're going to keep that representation at least for now) - add tests for the new compareTo method and a few previously missed unrelated cases

Implement the FlexiGridLayoutManager which lays out components in a grid where the width and column of each grid cell is sized based on the space actually required by the components in that cell's row and column (in contrast, the GridLayout manager forces each cell's width to be the same and each cell's height to be the same). Each component is added to the underlying FlexiGridContainer with a constraint object which specifies the component's row and column within the grid as well as how the component should be justified within its cell should it's size be smaller than the space available (top, center, bottom and left, center, right).
Also implement the FlexiGridPanelModel which provides a somewhat high level interface to the FlexiGridLayoutManager. In particular, the FlexiGridPanelModel allows the easy insertion of new rows or new columns, depending on the FlexiGridPanelModel instance's orientation, either before or after specific rows or columns.
Taken together, these classes provide a relatively easy way to manage a rectangular grid of components.
The current version of the FlexiGridLayoutManager only takes each component's preferred width and height into account. This results in the width of each column being the maximum of the preferred widths of the elements in the column and the height of each column being the maximum of the preferred heights of the elements in each row. A future version with also take each component's minimum and maximum width and heights into account.
Minor changes to the Measure class to improve the formatting of its output.
Provide a way to specify if the default instance of the RandomCentral class should be a SecureRandom instance or 'merely' a Random instance. The default is to use a SecureRandom instance.

A considerably cleaned up and somewhat improved FlexiGridPanelModel.
Lots and lots of textual cleanup.

Stop using various APIs that were deprecated in Java 9 (mostly AWT APIs).
Implement the FlexiGridDivider class which provides a way to include "divider lines" in components being managed by the FlexiGridLayoutManager (strictly speaking, this is intended for use with the FlexiGridPanelModel although the actual support for it is in the layout manager part of the flexi-grid facility).
Various cleanup including a bit of reorganizing of classes and methods.

Rework the ObtuseCollections class.
Update FlexiGridPanelModel and LevenshteinDistanceUtil to work with the updated ObtuseCollections class.
A tiny bit of minor cleanup. Committing to keep in sync with Burke.

In Gowing, fix totally broken support for EntityNames and implement and cleanup support for String and EntityName arrays.
Make the Selector and Alternative classes a more complete 'model' of a combo-box.
Comment out a bunch of Logger.log{Msg,Err} calls.

Fix the handling of row selection in the tableutils classes. Selecting rows by calling CheckBoxRowWrapper.setSelected(boolean) now works in the sense that checkmarks are updated, the notifications occur, etc.
Make sure that logging messages sent to a LogsWindow are shown in the exact order that they are passed to the window.
Fix the EntityName de-serialization facility in Gowing.
Remap entity ids when packing via Gowing. This ensures that two requests to pack the same collection of objects will yield precisely the same save file (ignoring timestamps) if the objects being saved and their values have not changed. This makes it fairly easy to avoid saving a whole series of equivalent auto-save files.
Rename the LayoutTracer as the TracingLayoutManager. Minor cleanup.
Get rid of essentially all commented out lines. Cleanup some empty methods (generally, add a call to ObtuseUtil.doNothing()).
